⏱️ 2. Scheduler: Background Reminder Checker
Browsers don’t allow true background services, but you can implement a heartbeat scheduler:

Option A — setInterval
Runs every X minutes while the app is open.

        js
    setInterval(checkReminders, 60 * 1000); // every 1 minute
Option B — Visibility API
When the user returns to the tab, check reminders.

        js
    document.addEventListener("visibilitychange", () => {
        if (!document.hidden) checkReminders();
    });
Option C — Service Worker(optional)
Allows push‑style notifications even when the tab is closed.

🔍 3. Reminder Logic: What JS Must Do
    checkReminders()
Load all reminders from the active workspace

Compare due_date with Date.now()

If due → trigger notification

Mark reminder as “triggered”

Log event in chat history

    Example:

    js
    async function checkReminders() {
        const reminders = await dbGetAll("reminders");
        const now = Date.now();

        reminders.forEach(rem => {
            if (rem.status === "pending" && new Date(rem.due_date).getTime() <= now) {
                triggerReminder(rem);
                rem.status = "triggered";
                dbPut("reminders", rem);
            }
        });
    }
